A good place to start is by reading the docs thoroughly. It’s intimidating, but it will help you to ask more specific questions.

The general idea for PathPlanner is that it has two components. One is the GUI, which is an application that runs on your PC. This is the place where you’ll edit your paths and autos. One very important step is to make sure you modify the settings for your specific robot:
https://pathplanner.dev/gui-settings.html

The second component is the Library, which gets added to your robot code. Follow the docs for setup. One of the most important steps is setting up the AutoBuilder. This is also the most confusing step, so take your time and read carefully:
https://pathplanner.dev/pplib-build-an-auto.html#holonomic-swerve

Use extreme caution when attempting to run autos. Mistakes in configuration can cause the robot to do very unexpected (and dangerous) things. Start with the robot on blocks, manually confirming that the swerve modules can rotate and spin freely in all directions.

My recommendation is to create a test auto that travels only a couple feet forward in a perfectly straight line. Check the result against your expectations. If there’s a difference, use the difference to diagnose the problem. If the robot did what you expected, feel free to very carefully run it again on the actual floor. Now you can actually measure the distance the robot traveled against the distance it was supposed to travel.

Your second auto should be one that rotates 90 degrees but does not move at all. Repeat the validation. Your third auto can combine traveling forward in a straight line while rotating 90 degrees. Validate again. Keep going, but always build upon how you’ve been succesful before.

Good luck!

You may want to look at a codebase that already has PathPlanner implemented. A number of teams publish a starter template that isn’t too loaded-up with multiple subsystems and lots of game customizations. By using a template that has PathPlanner along with drivetrain simulation, you can try PathPlanner in simulation to get an idea of how it works before implementing in the robot codebase you are using.

You might want to check out the 5712 template or the 1218 template to see PathPlanner in code.
